<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=864387054&t=artid%3dc2d14c2d-3b55-4945-8fbc-6f56596e06c3%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=864387054&t=artid%3dc2d14c2d-3b55-4945-8fbc-6f56596e06c3%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>According to MEC Lesufi, there are 17 schools of specialization in Gauteng, 2 of which were recently launched.Curtis Nkondo School of Specialization was launched in 2016 in Soweto.Magaliesburg Secondary School was launched in 2017 in the West Rand.The Gauteng Department of Education aims to launch 8 new schools of specialization in the 2018/2019 period.“Rhodesfield Technical School will be launched as an Engineering School of Specialisation with an Aviation focus,” Lesufi said.“This school, close to OR Tambo International Airport, is in the Manufacturing, transport (aeronautics) and Logistics Corridor. As a province, we are taking a bold step and introducing a Maritime School in the Vaal area.  Mohloli will be a Maths, Science and ICT school with a focus on Maritime. SAMSA (South African Maritime Safety Authority) will be a major partner in this endeavour.“BMW is adopting 2 schools in Soshanguve. These schools will specialize in the skills needed for the automotive industry.  “NECSA (Nuclear Energy Corporation of South Africa) will adopt 2 schools in Attridgeville.“These Maths, Science and ICT schools will focus on the Nuclear field, with learners learning about isotopes that are used in curing cancer.  Learners and educators will be exposed to virtual reality and will be able to develop skills and competencies required by the ever changing and new Digital environment,” he said.
